  {
    "appId": "3050900",
    "cpu": "AMD Ryzen 7 9800X3D 8-Core",
    "duration": "severalHours",
    "gpu": "NVIDIA GeForce RTX 5090",
    "gpuDriver": "NVIDIA 595.71.05",
    "kernel": "7.0.3-1-cachyos",
    "notes": "The NVIDIA Vulkan driver on Blackwell GPUs (tested on RTX 5090 and RTX 5080, driver 595.45.04) reports a fixed subgroup size with no flexibility: minSubgroupSize = 32 maxSubgroupSize = 32\n\nPrevious generation Ada Lovelace GPUs reported minSubgroupSize = 16, allowing shaders requesting subgroup size 16 to compile successfully.\n\nThis causes a concrete problem for D3D12 games running on Linux through Proton (vkd3d-proton). Games with compute shaders that specify [WaveSize(16)] fail pipeline creation because vkd3d-proton validates the requested wave size against what the Vulkan driver reports: d3d12_device_validate_shader_meta: Required WaveSize range [16, 16], but supported range is [32, 32]. d3d12_pipeline_state_init_compute: Failed to create Vulkan compute pipeline, hr 0x80070057.\n\nThese same games work on Windows with Blackwell GPUs, meaning the Windows D3D12 driver handles WaveSize 16 (presumably by running at warp 32 with lane masking or similar emulation). The capability exists in NVIDIA\u2019s driver stack --- it\u2019s just not exposed through the Vulkan interface on Blackwell.\n\nThis is a regression from Ada Lovelace behavior and affects any D3D12 game using WaveSize 16 compute shaders when running through Vulkan-based translation layers.\n\nmore information: https://forums.developer.nvidia.com/t/blackwell-vulkan-driver-missing-wavesize-16-support-that-windows-d3d12-driver-provides/364204",
    "os": "CachyOS",
    "protonVersion": "10.0-3",
    "ram": "126 GB",
    "rating": "borked",
    "timestamp": 1778072218,
    "title": "ROMEO IS A DEAD MAN",
    "source": "protondb"
